WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.230 --> 00:00:03.330
TOM OGREN: I'm Tom Ogren.

00:00:03.330 --> 00:00:06.290
And I'm the author
of a number of books

00:00:06.290 --> 00:00:07.910
on plants and allergies.

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:12.360
And I've been studying this
for more than 30 years now.

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:16.850
And the question I'm asked
most often is, how did I

00:00:16.850 --> 00:00:18.510
get into this and why?

00:00:18.510 --> 00:00:20.450
Do I have terrible allergies?

00:00:20.450 --> 00:00:22.600
And I don't.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:25.920
But I've been married 48
years to the same lady.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:27.460
Her name's Yvonne.

00:00:27.460 --> 00:00:29.790
And she was 15 when I met her.

00:00:29.790 --> 00:00:33.680
And she was having
allergies and asthma.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:36.880
And that's how come she
wasn't able to run away.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:38.440
The asthma was slowing her down.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:44.940
But at some point in our life
we were buying another house.

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:50.380
And I had in my mind it
would be nice if I could--

00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:52.440
the landscape didn't impress me.

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:56.677
I was a horticulturalist
and a horticulture teacher

00:00:56.677 --> 00:00:57.385
and a landscaper.

00:00:57.385 --> 00:00:59.770
And I thought, what
if I landscape this so

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:03.930
nothing in this yard will
ever make Yvonne sick,

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:07.880
so at least she'll have
her own cocooned area.

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:11.840
And the more I thought about
it, the better I liked the idea.

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:19.550
And so I went out to buy a
book on allergy-free gardening.

00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:23.690
And the first librarian I asked
about it was at a university.

00:01:23.690 --> 00:01:25.310
And she laughed.

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:27.150
And I said, well,
what's so funny?

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:28.770
And she said, well
it's the gardens

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:32.280
that cause all the allergies.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:36.400
But I had already learned
a few things by that point.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:43.090
And I had learned at some
plants did and some didn't.

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:45.490
I didn't know all of
that at all, believe me.

00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:50.650
But I had been doing sniff
tests with my students

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:54.070
teaching landscape
gardening in a prison.

00:01:54.070 --> 00:01:57.760
And we didn't beat
them or anything

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:59.050
to make them do the sniff.

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:01.840
It was voluntary
and I did it myself.

00:02:01.840 --> 00:02:07.420
But the very first plant--
in fact, the thing that

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:12.780
got the idea in my head
is my sister Rachel,

00:02:12.780 --> 00:02:13.860
she lives in Berkeley.

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:16.250
She likes to get me
to come up and do

00:02:16.250 --> 00:02:19.570
landscaping work for free
whenever she can, you know?

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:21.800
She's got her own expert
and the price is right.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:24.725
And so I was up there
doing some work for her

00:02:24.725 --> 00:02:27.436
and put in water lines
and so on in Berkeley.

00:02:27.436 --> 00:02:28.560
And everybody was sneezing.

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:29.550
It was spring time.

00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:33.870
And she was having asthma.

00:02:33.870 --> 00:02:36.514
And a week later,
I was driving home.

00:02:36.514 --> 00:02:37.680
And I was thinking about it.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:39.735
I live in San Luis Obispo.

00:02:39.735 --> 00:02:41.060
And I was thinking about.

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:43.490
And I thought, you know--
because at this point

00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:47.320
I was still thinking
allergies were psychosomatic,

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:50.640
because I had read
a book by an MD

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:53.050
about psychosomatic illnesses.

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:56.920
And he basically claimed that
asthma and allergies were

00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:00.950
a head trip and that if you
really had your act together

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:01.960
you wouldn't have them.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:05.340
And since I didn't have them,
I believed it, you know.

00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:07.800
So I would tell
my poor wife when

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.246
she'd have an
asthma attack, well,

00:03:09.246 --> 00:03:10.835
why don't you get
your act together?

00:03:10.835 --> 00:03:12.200
It's just a terrible thing.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:15.070
And so when I finally
did get into it,

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:16.700
I felt very guilty, of course.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.630
But the moment, that sort
of ah moment when I suddenly

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:24.510
felt guilty was I'm driving
back from Rachel's to San Luis

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:25.010
Obispo.

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:26.210
And I'm thinking of this.

00:03:26.210 --> 00:03:29.962
And I thought, what-- and
I knew nothing, really.

00:03:29.962 --> 00:03:30.920
I knew a lot of plants.

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:32.086
I was a good horticulturist.

00:03:32.086 --> 00:03:33.436
But I knew nothing.

00:03:33.436 --> 00:03:37.230
I thought, what if we go with
my students and we all sniff,

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:39.990
we start one flower and
everybody in the class sniffs.

00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:44.540
We do another, and we record,
see if anything does anything.

00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:47.415
And so I explained it to
the class on Monday morning.

00:03:47.415 --> 00:03:48.290
They were like, yeah.

00:03:48.290 --> 00:03:49.650
Yeah, that's a good idea.

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:50.930
Let's try it.

00:03:50.930 --> 00:03:54.080
And so the first flower
we ever did was pansies.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:57.350
And everybody in the whole
class, maybe 30 guys,

00:03:57.350 --> 00:04:00.000
they all sniffed
pansies, including me.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:00.665
Nothing.

00:04:00.665 --> 00:04:03.280
And we did some double dianthus.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:04.680
And everybody sniffed it.

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:05.300
Nothing.

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:09.840
And already I'm thinking, see,
direct right in their face,

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:10.530
nothing.

00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:13.610
And then they were growing
a bunch of bottlebrush

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:15.380
and we had them in gallon cans.

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:16.250
They're flowering.

00:04:16.250 --> 00:04:17.864
And I sniffed it, nothing.

00:04:17.864 --> 00:04:21.350
And my foreman
sniffed it, nothing.

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:23.770
Gave it to this one
big muscle-bound,

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:26.240
tattooed tough guy
and he sniffed it.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:30.020
And he sneezed so
hard, it like almost

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:32.030
knocked everybody
including him down.

00:04:32.030 --> 00:04:34.120
And everybody was
like, whoa, you know.

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:35.870
And everybody thought
it was really funny.

00:04:35.870 --> 00:04:38.700
But by the time we
went around the class,

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:41.610
I think we had a
dozen guys sneezing.

00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:43.330
And this was on Monday.

00:04:43.330 --> 00:04:45.550
And they don't give you
Allegra or Zyrtec or Claritin

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:47.250
in the prison.

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:49.110
And on Friday,
some of these guys

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:51.700
were still sneezing,
off of one direct sniff

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:52.940
off that bottlebrush.

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:55.670
Now as soon as that
happened, I was like,

00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:57.155
oh, this is not psychosomatic.

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:04.070
This isn't something just
most-- and the doctor

00:05:04.070 --> 00:05:06.490
had said it mostly
affected women,

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:11.670
because they were hysterical,
or prone to hysteria.

00:05:11.670 --> 00:05:15.890
And for years I would never even
admit this part of the story,

00:05:15.890 --> 00:05:18.440
because I found it
embarrassing, as I should have.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:22.550
But I guess enough
time has passed.

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:24.610
But that was my motivation.

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:29.240
And so when they laughed at
me about a book about it,

00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:32.270
I thought, well, I'll
just figure it out myself.

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:34.140
And I started studying.

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:36.730
This was pre-computers,
and I soon

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:41.550
had stacks and stacks of
things off my typewriters.

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:44.140
And then people started
finding I was doing this work.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:46.890
And so they would ask
me about some plant.

00:05:46.890 --> 00:05:51.305
I would have to dig through
all these unorganized files.

00:05:51.305 --> 00:05:53.410
And at one point, I
decided I was just

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:57.110
going to start doing all
the landscape plants A to Z

00:05:57.110 --> 00:05:59.280
if it took me 10 years.

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:02.760
And it took me 12 years, A to Z.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:05.340
And somewhere along
the line I decided

00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:08.690
I would rank them, 1
to 10, every plant.

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:10.775
I developed this
whole criteria list

00:06:10.775 --> 00:06:14.780
that would use close to
140 different criteria.

00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:16.650
And that's called OPALS.

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:19.639
And so a person could
know no horticulture.

00:06:19.639 --> 00:06:21.180
They could see the
name of the plant,

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:24.470
look it up, see it's
an OPALS 3, 1 being

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:26.480
the best, 10 being the worst.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:28.360
They could go, ah, 3,
I could live with that.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:31.750
And that's simplified it.

00:06:31.750 --> 00:06:34.130
My brother Paul told me,
yeah, get some laughs.

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:38.550
Well, I'm doing better at
that than I expected already.

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:40.440
Anyhow, I started
thinking about it.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:42.900
And I'll get in depth
here in a minute.

00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:45.260
But I started thinking
about this talk.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:51.799
And I thought, well,
I'm getting to the point

00:06:51.799 --> 00:06:53.340
where I've been
studying this so long

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:56.920
and I've given so
many talks on it

00:06:56.920 --> 00:07:00.820
and I have been published on
it in "The New York Times,"

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:03.660
last week in
"Scientific American."

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:05.910
I've been published
three, four times

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:09.725
in "New Scientist," all
sorts of great publications

00:07:09.725 --> 00:07:10.350
and everything.

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:12.680
And things are
starting to happen.

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:14.560
But I'm getting impatient.

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:16.630
And I thought, well,
I'm coming to Google.

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:20.540
And Google is known to hire the
brainiest people in the world,

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:25.790
and then to coddle them with
free lunches and free lattes

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:27.450
and stuff, you know.

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:30.440
And I noticed when I was
getting my coffee that there

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.160
was a-- or somewhere
here, yeah, there

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:35.949
was a little sign about
allergens in your food.

00:07:35.949 --> 00:07:38.240
And I thought, well, you
know, that's worth mentioning.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:39.906
They're worried about
the food allergens

00:07:39.906 --> 00:07:43.614
but nobody seems to care about
the allergens in the air.

00:07:43.614 --> 00:07:45.030
And by the way,
the food allergens

00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.110
are all related to
the pollen allergens.

00:07:47.110 --> 00:07:49.820
That's usually how you end up
getting the food allergens.

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:52.230
They're all cross-reactive.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:57.610
And so I thought the focus in
my mental head about this talk

00:07:57.610 --> 00:08:00.380
is going to be to
challenge Google.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:05.700
So Google, I
challenge Google here.

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:07.610
I'm quite serious about it.

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:09.320
I talk to people
and I say, OK, I'm

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:10.550
going to give a Google talk.

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:13.360
And they go like,
oh, that's awesome.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:17.380
And you ask people what
do they think about Google

00:08:17.380 --> 00:08:20.690
and they say, innovative.

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:23.410
They say, really smart.

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:26.830
They say, make things happen.

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:30.910
They say, they like a challenge.

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:36.900
And so my challenge would be
we take this very complicated

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:39.429
Google landscape-- and I
came up here a few weeks ago

00:08:39.429 --> 00:08:41.900
and spent some
time looking at it.

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:46.090
And we take this very
complicated, actually quite

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:49.320
allergenic landscape
and we transform it

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:55.930
into the most allergy-friendly
landscape in California,

00:08:55.930 --> 00:09:00.790
the most allergy-friendly
landscape in the United States,

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:04.850
the most healthiest,
allergy-friendly landscape

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:05.770
in the entire world.

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:07.450
And we do it right
here at Google so

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.050
that the people
that work at Google

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.570
will be the ones that
benefit the most.

00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:16.000
Now as I get into this, you'll
see that my talk is a lot more

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.300
than just about allergies.

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:20.570
Not to minimize allergies,
for people that have

00:09:20.570 --> 00:09:22.450
them they can be miserable.

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:25.720
Fire away there, Stewart.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:26.570
All right.

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:30.128
That's a picture I took.

00:09:30.128 --> 00:09:32.520
The pollen didn't
come from my house.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:34.330
This is at my house.

00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:36.880
And in the background,
by the way,

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:38.650
there's the largest
dawn redwood,

00:09:38.650 --> 00:09:42.700
Metasequoia glyptostroboides
in the entire United

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:43.860
States in my front yard.

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:46.400
It's cracking my
foundation and everything.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:47.710
I can't do anything about it.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:49.260
It's ruining my sewer pipes.

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:52.000
But it's the biggest one
in the United States.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.080
And the pollen comes
off-- this thing

00:09:55.080 --> 00:10:00.260
was parked next to a row of male
juniper bushes that showered it

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:03.470
and-- OK, flip, Stewart.

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:05.400
The story behind this.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:07.590
Two years ago, Johnson
&amp; Johnson hired

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:11.690
me to drive-- to go
coast to coast in Canada

00:10:11.690 --> 00:10:19.220
and do an allergy audit
of their urban forests

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:21.180
in the 11 largest cities.

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:23.600
So I start on Vancouver
Island and I drove my truck

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:25.820
all the way to Halifax.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:27.980
And in each city I
spent a week or two just

00:10:27.980 --> 00:10:30.730
walking around with a
clipboard and a camera

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:34.130
and binoculars for looking
up in these tall trees,

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:36.250
and sexing trees.

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:40.630
And I was in a hotel
room in Toronto.

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:42.520
Now an ash tree is
a big massive tree.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:46.210
There are literally thousands
of them right here at Google.

00:10:46.210 --> 00:10:48.340
And they're separate sex,
so one tree is all male

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.410
and one is all female.

00:10:51.410 --> 00:10:54.260
Probably 99% of them
at Google are male.

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:57.830
The males produce the
pollen, not the females.

00:10:57.830 --> 00:11:00.420
So I picked a couple of
these little clusters

00:11:00.420 --> 00:11:02.571
that were not shedding pollen.

00:11:02.571 --> 00:11:04.110
I brought them up
to my hotel room

00:11:04.110 --> 00:11:05.830
and I set them on
a piece of paper.

00:11:05.830 --> 00:11:13.020
And I printed out something,
or maybe they did that.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:16.640
But the next day when I gave
them a little tap, that's

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:17.380
how it looked.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:20.200
That's how much pollen
was just coming off

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:21.630
a couple of little clusters.

00:11:21.630 --> 00:11:26.440
Now, on a big tree, there's tens
of thousands of these clusters.

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:27.360
Fire away.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:31.290
All right.

00:11:31.290 --> 00:11:34.340
I threw this up here
because I'm not an MD.

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:35.415
I'm not a PhD.

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:42.060
I'm a horticulturalist
with extreme deep interest

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:44.030
in health and allergies.

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:46.200
But I've been
shopping the new book.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:49.380
And I guess we can
only see part of this.

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:54.780
But these are some very,
very good big time allergists

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:59.320
around the world that are pretty
much saying that my work is

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:00.180
right on the money.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:04.550
But you notice it says,
alternative and complementary

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:07.300
approach to this.

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:10.050
And I'm not trying to take the
place of doctors or anything,

00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:10.980
believe me.

00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:13.800
But this is an alternative.

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:15.740
And it is complementary.

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:19.260
It will make everything
better big time.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:19.945
Go for that.

00:12:23.670 --> 00:12:28.775
Botanical sexism is what I'm--
I'm credited with discovering

00:12:28.775 --> 00:12:30.710
a number of things.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:32.900
And one of them is
botanical sexism.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:35.090
And this is the fact
that every time they

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:38.280
could make a choice between a
male and female bush or tree

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:41.290
in the cities, pretty
much everywhere

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:46.879
in the civilized world, from
New Zealand to Nova Scotia,

00:12:46.879 --> 00:12:48.170
they always went with the male.

00:12:48.170 --> 00:12:52.670
And that's because the females
drop seeds or pods or fruits

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:54.070
or something.

00:12:54.070 --> 00:12:55.620
But the males drop stuff too.

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:57.950
This is a male cedar tree.

00:12:57.950 --> 00:13:01.082
And that's pollen on the ground.

00:13:01.082 --> 00:13:04.580
I'm not going to get
too technical here,

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:08.240
but-- I guess I won't
even have a chance,

