00:29:55.670 --> 00:29:59.385
I just mentioned for a
second the one big change

00:29:59.385 --> 00:30:00.260
in the United States.

00:30:00.260 --> 00:30:04.260
When I was a little kid,
almost every street in America

00:30:04.260 --> 00:30:07.010
was lined with
American elm trees.

00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:09.400
They're big beautiful trees
and they grew over and made

00:30:09.400 --> 00:30:11.450
a canopy over the road.

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:13.330
I grew up on Pine
Street, which was

00:30:13.330 --> 00:30:15.170
line with these American elms.

00:30:15.170 --> 00:30:16.880
There was only one pine.

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.880
And street after
street was that way.

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:23.310
And then in the
'60s and the '70s,

00:30:23.310 --> 00:30:25.580
the Dutch Elm Disease came over.

00:30:25.580 --> 00:30:29.730
And it started killing these
trees off by the millions fast.

00:30:29.730 --> 00:30:32.480
And whole cities had no trees.

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:37.140
By then, the universities and
the USDA had gotten together

00:30:37.140 --> 00:30:40.780
and they were developing these
new smart trees, if you will,

00:30:40.780 --> 00:30:42.690
which were the male clones.

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:46.880
And so the USDA put out
more than 100 different

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:51.420
named clones of red maple
alone, plus a lot of hybrids,

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:54.350
every one of which was a male.

00:30:54.350 --> 00:30:56.780
This was going on at
the universities too.

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:02.030
And so this was the new
litter free landscaping.

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:05.800
But they had set the stage
for where we're at today.

